      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Why is my disc stack centrifuge vibrating excessively?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Excessive vibration is most commonly caused by an unbalanced bowl due to uneven sludge accumulation, worn or failed bearings, a bent spindle, or disc stack damage. The machine should be shut down immediately if vibration significantly increases, as continued operation risks catastrophic bowl failure.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What causes a disc stack centrifuge to make unusual noise?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Unusual noise includes grinding or rumbling (worn bearings), clicking or popping (debris in bowl or disc stack contact), squealing (belt or friction clutch wear), and knocking (loose bowl parts or damaged gear teeth). Any new or changed noise should be investigated immediately — most noise issues escalate quickly into serious mechanical failures.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Why does my disc centrifuge have a burning smell?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">A burning smell typically indicates overheated motor windings due to overloading, a slipping friction clutch generating frictional heat during startup, or overheated gear oil from insufficient lubrication. Each cause requires different corrective action — investigate immediately to prevent permanent damage.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Why does my disc centrifuge take too long to reach operating speed?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Slow startup is usually caused by a worn friction clutch, a seized or dragging bearing, or a motor losing power. Belt-driven machines may have a worn or incorrectly tensioned drive belt. If the friction clutch is worn, it will eventually fail to spin up the bowl at all — replace it before complete failure occurs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
